 Here is a code snippet in Python that generates a UUID v4 string:

```python
import uuid
uuid_str = str(uuid.uuid4())
print(uuid_str)
```

When you run this code, it will print a UUID v4 string like `3ba8a6c1-b97d-4e5f-a20a-b8d5b1c23456`. You can replace the print statement with your desired variable assignment if needed.

For other programming languages, you can use their respective libraries to generate UUIDs. For example, in Java:

```java
import java.util.UUID;
UUID uuid = UUID.randomUUID();
String uuidStr = uuid.toString();
System.out.println(uuidStr);
```

In JavaScript (Node.js):

```javascript
const { v4: uuidv4 } = require('uuid');
console.log(uuidv4());
```
